gapminder

Extreme Temperatures Data

This analysis works with a data set of the number of people injured or killed due to extreme temperatures during the given year in each country.

Get the right packages

#install.packages('ggplot2')
library(ggplot2)

#install.packages('tidyr')
library(tidyr)

#install.packages('dplyr')
library(dplyr)

Realized years need to be their own variable (i.e. gather() from tidyr)

xheatdata2 <- gather(xheatdata,"Year","Fatalities",na.rm = TRUE, -1)
head(xheatdata2)
##       Country Year Fatalities
## 1 Afghanistan 1971          0
## 2     Albania 1971          0
## 3     Algeria 1971          0
## 4   Argentina 1971          0
## 5   Australia 1971          0
## 6     Austria 1971          0
  # it worked! and dropped NAs 

# convert year into int variable
xheatdata2$Year <- as.numeric(xheatdata2$Year)
xheatdata2$Count <- (xheatdata2$Fatalities > 0)
head(xheatdata2)
##       Country Year Fatalities Count
## 1 Afghanistan 1971          0 FALSE
## 2     Albania 1971          0 FALSE
## 3     Algeria 1971          0 FALSE
## 4   Argentina 1971          0 FALSE
## 5   Australia 1971          0 FALSE
## 6     Austria 1971          0 FALSE
#xheatdata2[xheatdata2 == 0] <- NA
#na.omit(object = xheatdata2)

Summary of fatalities data

summary(xheatdata2$Fatalities)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
##        0        0        0    34470        0 77000145
# The vast majority of data is 0. There is an enormous outlier for one country: 77000145 

# What happens when you remove that outlier? 
xheatdata3 <- xheatdata2[!xheatdata2$Fatalities == 77000145,]
summary(xheatdata3$Fatalities)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##       0       0       0    5569       0 3000517
# the next high outlier is at 3000517.

See how years of extreme events fluctuated over time

# histogram of fatalities in all countries across all time
qplot(x = Fatalities, data = xheatdata2, binwidth = 0.1, color = I('blue'),
      xlab = '# of fatalities',
      ylab = 'Count', 
      fill = I('#099DD9')) +
  scale_x_log10()
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous x-axis
## Warning: Removed 2407 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

# boxplot of same data
qplot(x = factor(0), y = Fatalities, data = xheatdata2, color = I('blue'),
      xlab = '',
      ylab = 'Fatalities', 
      fill = I('#D909A1'),
      geom = 'boxplot') + 
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0,1))

  # not helpful because so many values are at 0

Preview of 2D analysis: China vs US

ggplot(data=xheatdata2[xheatdata2$Country=='China',], aes(x=Year, y=Fatalities)) +
  geom_line()+ 
  scale_y_log10()
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous y-axis

ggplot(data=xheatdata2[xheatdata2$Country=='United States',], aes(x=Year, y=Fatalities)) +
  geom_line()+ 
  scale_y_log10()
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous y-axis

Ideas for the future:

  1. Compare early years to future years. E.g.

    early_pts = which(xheatdata2[‘Year’]<1990) late_pts = which(xheatdata2[‘Year’]>= 1990)

  2. Compare China and US

    china_pts = which(xheatdata2[‘Country’] == ‘China’) us_pts = which(xheatdata2[‘Country’] == ‘United States’)
